properties.Name: EEZ
properties.Description:
Within the Gulf of Tonkin, the Vietnam-China maritime boundary is demarcated in a treaty. South of Hainan Island and through the Paracels, where the distance between the Vietnamese and Chinese baselines is less than 400 nautical miles, a median line was used to draw the extent of Vietnams exclusive economic zone (EEZ).

South of the Paracel Islands, Vietnams EEZ was drawn to its maximum 200 nautical mile extent into the South China Sea. This is consistent with the limit of Vietnams EEZ shown in the 2009 joint submission with Malaysia to the UN Commission on the Limits of the Continental Shelf.

Opposite Indonesias EEZ generated from the Natuna Islands, Vietnams EEZ was drawn along the continental shelf demarcation line agreed to in 2003. While Indonesia does not recognize this line as the extent of its EEZ, a member of our International Expert Panel advised us that Vietnam would prefer that the two countries upgrade the line to apply to its EEZ.

West of the boundary with Indonesia exists an area covered by a joint petroleum exploration and exploitation memorandum signed in 1992 by Malaysia and Vietnam. Without prejudice to final demarcation of either the continental shelf or the EEZ, the two countries agreed to jointly conduct hydrocarbon exploration within a sliver of the sea. We used the further edge of that defined area, points C, D, and E in the memorandum, as the maximum extent of Vietnams EEZ.

The Thai-Vietnamese maritime boundary was delimited in a 1997 agreement. Southeast of this boundary segment and northwest of the Malay-Vietnamese joint exploration area, Vietnams EEZ overlaps with a Malay-Thai joint development area. A median line was drawn to show the extent of Vietnams EEZ in this area. The boundary with Cambodia was drawn along the equidistant line between the two countries, although Cambodia is known to have rejected the equidistant line in the past.

Vietnams straight baselines were drawn from coordinates submitted to the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea. A 12-nm territorial sea was subsequently drawn around these baselines.
